40 2021-01-17 constipation, abdominal discomfort, abdominal distension Patient with PMH of depression and GERD who presented 1/8 with constipation, abdominal discomfort an... Read more
Close
Patient with PMH of depression and GERD who presented 1/8 with constipation, abdominal discomfort and worsening dyspnea. Symptoms began around 12/29. COVID vaccine 12/19. Previously quite active, marathon runner, gained some weight over last couple years but was still in good enough shape to complete 10K in New Orleans in early February. In late February, had a flu-like illness, as did one of his friends from church. 2020 was hard on him - weight gain, decreased activity, stress, overall deconditioning. No issues apart from sore arm after COVID vaccine 12/19 but then starting getting abdominal fullness/discomfort around 12/29, which steadily worsened, also develop worsening dyspnea on slight exertion. No known sick contacts.. Work-up notable for pericardial effusion, pleural effusions. Echo with severe diffuse LV hypokinesis, concern raised for myocarditis. COVID PCR negative, serology negative. RVP negative. . Concern raised that COVID vaccine may have played a role in myocarditis. He was found to have the following conditions Acute heart failure with reduced EF NYHA FC II, non-ischemic cardiomyopathy. Myocarditis appears subacute per MRI hypertension obesity small pericardial effusion- asysmptomatic no pericarditis suspected obstructive sleep apnea. .Started on the following medications. Continue Carvedilol 12.5mg BID, Farxiga 5mg daily, Digoxin 0.125mg daily, Entresto 97-103mg BID, and Spironolactone 25mg daily. Per MD note. While it remains uncertain, team is doubtful COVID vaccine played a role in his cardiac issues. Given the MRI findings are not acute, more likely that the cardiac insult occurred weeks to months ago - potentially in the setting of the February 2020 illness. Perhaps his "deconditioning" in 2020 was related to worsening cardiac function. Nevertheless, will hold on 2nd COVID vaccine dose given absence of a clear explanation for his myocarditis. conversation with team will continue to determine if candidate for second covid vaccine. If consensus is that myocarditis pre-dated vaccine, might be able to proceed with dose 2 of vaccine.

Patient presents to ED on 1/14/2021 with respiratory arrest and started around 1300. Per EMS, reportedly told fiance that he had taken some sleeping pills and was going to go to sleep. EMS was called after the patient was found unresponsive about 15 minutes later. Family attempted to do CPR. Upon EMS arrival to the patient's home, patient had a pulse, was in respiratory distress with agonal breathing. They also reported emesis in the airway. EMS performed nasal intubation and administered 10 mg IV Narcan en route. Upon arrival to the hospital, patient was moving arms more and gritting teeth. Patient had movements of decerebrate posturing of arms intermitting with a relaxed posture. GCS was 4 on arrival. Patient is currently still in ICU and has been extubated.

40 2021-03-03 difficulty swallowing throat swelling, shortness of breath Patient given first dose of Pfizer COVID 19 vaccine at vaccine ... Read more
Close
throat swelling, shortness of breath Patient given first dose of Pfizer COVID 19 vaccine at vaccine clinic. Within 15 minute observation window, patient reported shortness of breath, difficulty swallowing, and throat swelling. Epinephrine 0.3 mg IM autoinjector was administered and emergency response team was called. Patient was transported to ED and was fully alert, with no respiratory distress or other complaints upon arrival to ED. Was given diphenhydramine 50 mg IVP, methylprednisolone 125 mg IVP, and fluids. Blood work and chest xray obtained. No notable findings. Patient was discharged from ED with prednisone dosepak, cetirizine, and famotidine outpatient prescriptions.

41 2021-05-09 abdominal pain, nausea, diarrhea, abdominal pain upper On April 18 and 19, following my 2nd injection, I had very bad chills and could not get warm. I was ... Read more
Close
On April 18 and 19, following my 2nd injection, I had very bad chills and could not get warm. I was nauseous although I did not vomit. On April 22, I began having severe sharp stabbing pains just to the right of my belly button. It felt like I was being stabbed with a very hot knife, and after about 15-90 seconds, it would go away. Anytime I reached for something, bent over, twisted, turned or tried to hug someone, I would get this same pain and it would double me over in pain. On Monday April 26 at 7pm, I finally checked into the Emergency Room at the direction of my Primary Doctor. They did a bunch of blood work on me and sent me for a CT Scan of my abdomen. All of the blood work came back in normal ranges, and the CT Scan showed my appendix was "borderline" according to the surgeon. They consulted with Dr and decided to admit me for a surgical consult and further examination. They gave me fluids and morphine through an IV for the first 24 - 36 hrs, and then switched to Norco by mouth. I continued having pain throughout my stay. On Thursday, April 29, they took me to surgery for "exploratory surgery" with the intention of removing my appendix and looking around to see if anything else stood out to them that would cause me this pain. They stated my appendix had scar tissue on it and they removed it, but said they did not know if this would stop the pain I was having. On Friday April 30, I was released from the hospital at approximately 6pm. By 9pm on Friday, I began having those same sharp, stabbing, burning pains in my abdomen again, now to the right of my belly button again and further towards my right side. I also had sharp burning pain in the inside of my upper right arm, between my bicep and tricep muscles. This pain continued on through the weekend occurring more frequently and more severe. On Monday morning at about 1:30am, I woke up with severe abdominal pains all over and went into the bathroom. I had diarrhea and nausea and felt like I was going to vomit. Between 1:30am and 7:30am, I went to the bathroom 6 times. I went to work on Monday and continued having abdominal pains and diarrhea all day and night. On Tuesday, I went to the bathroom a total of 17 times. On Wednesday, I saw my primary Dr., who examined my abdomen and pains. He suggested I take immodium for the diarrhea and a supplement for muscle pain, as he felt this was the cause of my pain. On Wednesday, I went to the bathroom 21 times and was very nauseaus. I started the Imodium and it had no effect on me whatsoever. On Thursday, I had to call off work because I couldn't stop using the bathroom. By 4pm, I had been to the bathroom 18 times. I returned to the ER. They took a stool sample and did an ultrasound in the ER. They decided to admit me again for surgical consult and pain management. On Friday, Dr ordered another ultrasound of my abdomen, specifically my gallbladder, kidney, and liver. He also sent me for a CT Scan with contrast. They completed a total lab workup of my blood. All of these results came back normal, and nothing on the images showed anything wrong with my organs. On Saturday May 8, Dr came to the hospital to examine me. He stated everything related to my GI was fine. He asked if I have back pain, which I told him I do. At this time, I was in extreme pain and I couldn't even touch my skin. Dr attempted to examine my abdomen, and just by placing his hand on my stomach, I screamed in pain. He then put his hand behind my back and pushed a little, and it cause extreme pain in my abdomen. At this time, Dr suggested that maybe the pain is caused by something going on in my back. Maybe a pinched nerve or something. He ordered an X-ray of my upper and lower spine. Later that day, the results of the X-ray came back and showed there was nothing wrong with my spine. With these results, Dr then ordered an MRI of my lumbar and thoracic spine. On Sunday May 9 at 1030am, I was taken to radiology for an MRI. The initial report shows that I do not have any pinched nerves and nothing notable that would cause this type of pain in my body. As of now, no diagnosis or explanation for the pain I am experiencing. The pain is gradually getting worse and at times I am unable to move at all without extreme severe pain in my body. At times, my right groin hurts and I am unable to stand on my feet, as it feels as if I have pulled a groin muscle. The pain in my abdomen takes my breath away and feels like I am being set on fire in that area of my body. The pain no longer goes away and is constant, but moves throughout my right side from my groin to my shoulder only. I am not able to put my right arm behind my back because I get this pain in the back of my shoulder area. This pain is only on my right side at this time. So far, there is no explanation for this pain. I never had anything like this until I got the vaccine.

Once outside his door, I noticed he was finishing taking X-Rays when he suddenly had another seizure.

After being seated with RN, he expressed concern about receiving his 2nd dose due to the reactions he experienced after receiving his 1st dose. RN requested Lead RN speak with the client regarding his concerns. At 1720 Lead RN spoke to client. The swelling continued below his axillary down the left side of his abdomen and onto the left side of his back. Client stated the pain level was a 4 on a scale of 0-10. He also stated there was no discoloration or redness in any of the areas where he experienced swelling. On day 10 the left side of the client?s neck began to swell. He also started to experience discomfort at the injection site and arm fatigue. Client stated at no time did he experience any trouble breathing, shortness of breath, or chest pain. Client stated he has been dieting and lost 145 lbs. in the last year. He previously had high blood pressure, but no longer does. He also stated the only other underlying conditions he has is a thyroid problem (hypothyroidism), and he is not medication compliant. Over the last 6 months he has only taken his levothyroxine intermittently. In the last 2 months he has not taken any of his levothyroxine until a few days ago. Client takes no other medication, but is allergic to penicillin-based antibiotics. Client stated he gets dizzy, hallucinates, and swells up in various places on his body. However, he does not experience shortness of breath or trouble breathing. Client did not take any medication for the side effects he experienced after receiving his first Pfizer injection or seek medical treatment. Client stated all the swelling began to subside on day 17. Lead RN performed a medical consult with Clinical Care Coordinator who authorized moving forward with administering client a Pfizer 2nd dose in the opposite arm with a 30-minute observation. Prior to RN administering vaccine, Lead RN educated client on normal vs adverse effects of the vaccine. Lead RN confirmed with client that he has access to a HCP for follow-up, if needed. Lead RN also recommended client follow-up with his HCP regarding his hyperthyroid condition. Lead RN instructed client to seek emergency care if he experienced shortness of breath, trouble breathing, or chest pain at any time after leaving the vaccination facility.

Close
Right ear pain started on the Wednesday afternoon, two days after Vaccine shot. By Friday evening the ear pain was intense and it had moved below the ear to lymphnode area. Saturday, his ear was really swollen and red. He went to the Urgent Care and they prescribed an antibiotic Cephalexin thinking it could be some sort of ear infection or insect bite. Sunday morning he woke up with his face droopy. We tried to get an appt. with Urgent Care, but they sent us to the ER. The ER did a physical assessment and concluded he had an ear infection and Bells Palsy. The prescribed another antibiotic Doxycycline, an antiviral Famciclovir and a steroid of prednisone. By Monday he was extremely nauseas and had started having vertigo. We went to Urgent Care and they prescribed him Ondansetron for nausea and made the assessment that he had Shingles in his ear. We saw PCP on Wednesday and he assessed that this was a zoster ear infection causing facial paralysis and vertigo, also known as a rare condition called Ramsay Hunt Syndrome and that it was most likely attributed to his Covid vaccine shot and not to get the second vaccine shot. The Dr. took him off the antibiotics and put him on a higher dose of prednisone, a different antiviral (valacyclovir) and Meclizine for vertigo symptoms. He sent referrals for Neurology, ENT and Eye Dr. He saw the Neurologist that Friday and he concurred Ramsay Hunt Syndrome, most likley from Covid Vaccine and do not get the second vaccine shot. The neurologist referred him to Physical Therapy to treat his vestibular issues. He ordered an MRI and some blood work. We are still waiting for the results. We saw an ENT an he had him have a hearing test which showed moderate high frequency hearing loss. The ENT prescribed Gabapentin for the ear and face pain. He started to see a physical therapist this week, he had his MRI on Wednesday and we see the ENT again on Monday. He has no improvement yet, other than the nausea has subsided.

45 2021-04-05 difficulty swallowing Within 60 seconds of receiving the injection, I experienced moderate breathing difficulty. After 1... Read more
Close
Within 60 seconds of receiving the injection, I experienced moderate breathing difficulty. After 10-20 minutes, I noticed that my throat felt slightly swollen (slight difficulty swallowing). Due to a hyperallergic event that occurred about 12 years ago, I occasionally run into something that triggers the respiratory effect - although usually the reaction is milder than that caused by the vaccine. However, the throat swelling is new. I took a single puff of an Albuterol inhaler around 5 minutes after the injection, but it had no effect (usually the case for me when the cause is allergic in nature). About 37 minutes after the injection, medical staff advised me to take an antihistamine. I took approximately 6 mg of doxylamine succinate (orally). However, by this point, the breathing had already started to ease slightly. Approximately 30 minutes later, my breathing was back to normal and the throat inflamation was gone. It's uncertain how much of that would have occurred through time alone and how much of it was the antihistamine starting to take effect. My BP was very high when measured during treatment. Partially explained by the albuterol inhaler combined with pseudoephedrine taken earlier in the day, along with anxiety and exertion from the event itself.

I received my first Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine shot on March 5, 2021, and my second shot on March 26, 2021. After my first shot, I had minor chills, no fever, and was a little tired for two days. However, approximately 12 hours after my second shot, I had a 101.0 F fever, with a heart rate of 105. I did not take any fever reducing medicine. I had a fever for two days, and slight elevation in my temperature on the third day. My heart rate decreased over the second and third day, and went back to my normal 50s-60, four days after my second shot. I had slight nausea the first day, and a loss of appetite two additional days. My appetite is now back to normal. Furthermore, I had a lot of soreness in my lower back, neck, shoulders, and knees that lasted 5 or 6 days after my second shot. Also, I had a low-level intermittent headache the first day after the second shot. In addition, I had significant chills that lasted 10 days after the second shot. My chief complaint is feeling very lightheaded / unsteady when in a standing position. Also, my exercise routine has suffered the past month. I only walk 15 to 20 minutes and feel very tired. Certainly, not a normal feeling for me. I feel very tired over the past month and a half since my second shot. I have checked my EKG a few times over the past 6 weeks. It is my normal EKG, (RBBB and LAFB) and remains unchanged.

On 5/20/21 the patient was at home with his mother when he had acute nausea, light-headedness, and abdominal pain. He presented to the ED by ambulance. Excerpt from ED notes od MD follows: "Initial ED interventions: iv fluids, low dose iv ativan, iv toradol, iv zofran. ED course: patient arrives very anxious, writhing on bed, difficult to redirect. With chronic tonicity, not seizing. Mother arrives, and he recognizes her, seems to be consoled somewhat by her presence, but she is unable to direct him, and describes his behavior as irregular, and events acute this evening at her home. Patient rests, and then HR decrease to 50s on monitior and patient found to be pulseless - I immediately start chest compressions, and achieve ROSC after PEA arrest with administration of EPI/compressions. Patient intubated per procedure note without complication. L femoral central attained per procedure note without complication. CPR performed over ED course intermittently (always PEA arrest) with ROSC achieved with administration of EPI, EPI drip started in addition to sedation meds, and iv fluids. No obvious STEMI on ECG to administer lytics, with suspicion of dissection and AAA prominent. I am able to stabilze and accompany patient to CT suite, where I recognize B/L massive PE immediately. I discuss with Dr. of Cardiology, who agrees with admininstration of alteplase. I disucss risks with mother who consents verbally. Patient without response to alteplase, and with continued pattern of PEA arrest following bradycardia. I discuss etiology of presentation with mother,and that patient is with very poor prognosis of survival, and likely poorer prognosis of neurological status, and patient is made comfort care, and fentanyl drip increased, patient is taken off of ventilation and drips. Pronounced deceased at 22:00. MDM: Initial concern for but not limited to appendicitis, AAA, diverticulitis, renal stones, pyelonephritis, musculoskeletal pain, pancreatitis, toxic ingestion, ACS, obstruction, perforation, sepsis (2/2 PNA, UTI, meningitis, intra-abdominal infection), AAA, dissection, PE - as ED course progresses, differential narrows and consider more likely PEA arrest secondary to ACS, PE, dissection, AAA, necrotic pancreatitis, tension PNX (less likely). Considered but do not suspect seizures, stroke. Imaging studies reviewed - CXR with ETT in place, no acute pathology. CTA chest/A/P remarkable for massive proximal B/L PE. Labs reviewed. ECGs without STEMI, with sinus tach initially, LBBB after initial ROSC, and then AFib in RVR on subsequent ECG. Per above, patient suffered massive B/L PE, with subsequent cardiac arrest, despite heoric efforts including thrombolysis. Death called art 22:00. Diagnosis: massive B/L PEs, PEA arrest. Disposition: deceased."

Case Comment/Senders Comment: The company has assessed the serious adverse events of COVID-19 pneumonia, acute respiratory failure, pulmonary arterial hypertension, influenza, fluid overload, mitral valve incompetence, and steroid diabetes as not related to Orenitram. The event of COVID-19 pneumonia was related to the ongoing SARS-CoV-2 pandemic, and the event influenza was related to seasonal Influenza B. The event acute respiratory failure was likely related to acute influenza, but was also possibly impacted by pulmonary insult from COVID-19 pneumonia, and underlying lupus associated with PAH. The event pulmonary arterial hypertension was likely an exacerbation of the underlying PAH due to the concurrent infections. The event mitral valve incompetence and fluid overload were likely related to cardiac dysfunction associated with the underlying chronic and progressive PAH. The event steroid diabetes was likely related to co-suspect medication Medrol, which was used as treatment for the lupus, although co-suspect medication nifedipine was possibly contributory to the event in view of its safety profile and as such cannot be excluded. Pfizer is a marketing authorization holder of [Nifedipine] in the country of incidence or the country where the product was purchased (if different). This may be a duplicate report if another marketing authorization holder of [Nifedipine] has submitted the same report to the regulatory authorities. Information on the batch/Lot number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the temporal association and the known safety profile, a possible contributory role of BNT162B2 to the development of drug ineffective, COVID-19, pneumonia, rash, pyrexia and diarrhoea cannot be excluded. Acute hypoxemic respiratory failure was secondary to COVID-19, therefore was also considered as related to BNT162B2. The other events were considered as due to underlying or intercurrent conditions and unrelated to BNT162B2. Steroid diabetes was considered as related to methylprednisolone and other events were unrelated to methylprednisolone. Oedema peripheral and limb discomfort were considered as related to nifedipine and other events were unrelated to nifedipine. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Case Comment/Senders Comment: The company has assessed the serious adverse events of COVID-19 pneumonia, acute respiratory failure, pulmonary arterial hypertension, influenza, fluid overload, mitral valve incompetence, and steroid diabetes as not related to Orenitram. The event of COVID-19 pneumonia was related to the ongoing SARS-CoV-2 pandemic, and the event influenza was related to seasonal Influenza B. The event acute respiratory failure was likely related to acute influenza, but was also possibly impacted by pulmonary insult from COVID-19 pneumonia , and underlying lupus associated with PAH. The event pulmonary arterial hypertension was likely an exacerbation of the underlying PAH due to the concurrent infections. The event mitral valve incompetence and fluid overload were likely related to cardiac dysfunction associated with the underlying chronic and progressive PAH. The event steroid diabetes was likely related to co-suspect medication Medrol, which was used as treatment for the lupus, although co-suspect medication nifedipine was possibly contributory to the event in view of its safety profile and as such cannot be excluded. The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the event with the suspect product was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment. No follow-up attempts are possible; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and the consistency with the known safety profile of the suspect product BNT162B2, events of COVID-19 pneumonia, Drug ineffective, Fever, Diarrhea could be related to the suspected drug of BNT162B2. All the other events are most likely related to an intercurrent or underlying condition which is not related to the suspected drug. The reported events are considered unlikely related to the suspected drug of Nifedipine. The events of Diabetes steroid-induced is most likely related to co-suspect medication Medrol, which was used as treatment for the lupus. All the other events are considered unlikely related to the suspected drug of Medrol. Medical history of ongoing Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH/ High BP disorder/ increased pressure of pulmonary circulation), ongoing Systemic lupus erythematosus, and ongoing Dyspnoea may provide explanations for some of the events (such as Pulmonary arterial hypertension, Volume overload, Mitral regurgitation, and Oedema peripheral). The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.
